">           Even if an artificially intelligent specie fell within the guidelines of "harmful" as defined previously, it would still be immoral for humanity to commit genocide on them. In the singularity, AI is considered living and conscious. When we murder something, it is essentially taking away their ability to live and to exist, without their consent. As a result, in her article "If Machines Can Think, Do They Deserve Civil Rights?", futurist scholar and science journalist Raya Bidshahri says that, if we extinguished a self-aware artificial intelligent, we would be infringing on the basic right to live. Additionally, once a machine is self-conscious and can demand or is aware that it would like rights, if humans then decided to reprogram them so that they no longer had consciousness, it would be immoral, since that would essentially be killing and refusing their right to survive and thrive. Bidshari also addresses counter arguments that say that, it would be preposterous to give AI rights since they would always be, at some level, programmed to be good or evil by humans. Yet, there are still debates regarding whether humans truly have free will. Many would agree that, regardless of whether or not it turns out that humans have free will or not, we should still have basic rights, such as living. Thus, it is immoral for humans to commit genocide on self-aware androids.</p>
